definition: "Coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10), also known as ubiquinone in its oxidized form and ubiquinol in its reduced form, is a fat-soluble molecule found in virtually every cell in the body — particularly in tissues with high energy demands: the heart, liver, kidneys, and skeletal muscle. CoQ10 serves two critical biological functions. First, it is an essential electron carrier in the mitochondrial electron transport chain (ETC) — specifically shuttling electrons between Complex I and III and between Complex II and III — making it indispensable for the production of ATP, the cell's primary energy currency. Second, CoQ10 is a potent lipid-soluble antioxidant that protects cell membranes and LDL particles from oxidative damage. CoQ10 is biosynthesized endogenously from mevalonate (the same pathway used by statins) and is also obtained from dietary sources, particularly meat and fish."
why_it_matters: "CoQ10 is one of the few nutrients where the case for testing and supplementation in specific populations is particularly strong. Two groups are at elevated risk for clinically meaningful CoQ10 depletion: people taking statin medications (which block the mevalonate pathway and reduce CoQ10 biosynthesis by 30–50%) and older adults (CoQ10 levels decline 30–50% between ages 20 and 80 as endogenous biosynthesis falls). In both groups, CoQ10 depletion may contribute to muscle symptoms, exercise intolerance, fatigue, and impaired cardiac function. Beyond these groups, CoQ10 insufficiency has been associated with heart failure, hypertension, mitochondrial dysfunction syndromes, and accelerated aging in multiple tissues."

